06286nam a22008895i 9780812296662DE-B159720210621102733.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210621t20192020pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808122966627 a10.9783/97808122966622doi  a(DE-B1597)531780  a(OCoLC)1143826180  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aHD6508b.W355 2020 7aPOL0130002bisacsh04a331.8811351732231 aWalker, Alexis N., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aDivided Unions :bThe Wagner Act, Federalism, and Organized Labor /cAlexis N. Walker. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2019] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (200 p.) :b8 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aAmerican Governance: Politics, Policy, and Public Law00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tChapter 1. Introduction -- tChapter 2. The Wagner Act: A Critical Exclusion -- tChapter 3. After Wagner (1936–1960): Life Without Collective Bargaining Rights -- tChapter 4. 1961: The Public Sector’s Watershed Moment -- tChapter 5. The 1970s: Labor Out of Alignment -- tChapter 6. The Late 1970s to the 2010s: Labor on the Decline -- tChapter 7. The 2010s: The Modern Assault Against Public Sector Unions -- tChapter 8. Conclusion: The Consequences of Labor’s Enduring Divide -- tAppendix: Interview Method Description -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe 2011 battle in Wisconsin over public sector employees' collective bargaining rights occasioned the largest protests in the state since the Vietnam War. Protestors occupied the state capital building for days and staged massive rallies in downtown Madison, receiving international news coverage for the events. Despite an unprecedented effort to oppose Governor Scott Walker's bill, Act 10 was signed into law on March 11, 2011, stripping public sector employees of many of their collective bargaining rights and hobbling government unions in Wisconsin. By situating the events of 2011 within the larger history of public sector unionism, Alexis N. Walker demonstrates how the passage of Act 10 in Wisconsin was not an exceptional moment, but rather the culmination of events that began over eighty years ago with the passage of the Wagner Act in 1935.Although explicitly about government unions, Walker's book argues that the fate of public and private sector unions are inextricably linked. She contends that the exclusion of public sector employees from the foundation of private sector labor law, the Wagner Act, firmly situated private sector law at the national level, while relegating public sector employees' efforts to gain collective bargaining rights to the state and local levels. She shows how private sector unions benefited tremendously from the national-level protections in the law while, in contrast, public sector employees' efforts progressed slowly, were limited to union friendly states, and the collective bargaining rights that they finally did obtain were highly unequal and vulnerable to retrenchment. As a result, public and private sector unions peaked at different times, preventing a large, unified labor movement. The legacy of the Wagner Act, according to Walker, is that labor remains geographically concentrated, divided by sector, and hobbled in their efforts to represent working Americans politically in today's era of rising economic inequality.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 0aCollective bargainingxGovernment employeeszUnited States. 0aCollective bargainingxLaw and legislationzUnited States. 0aGovernment employee unionszUnited States. 0aLabor unionsxLaw and legislationzUnited States. 0aLabor unionsxPolitical activityzUnited States. 0aLabor uni